<LP>
   DONALD TRUMP'S debt includes more than $500 million in
bank loans that he personally guaranteed, bankers say.
Lenders are increasingly seeking the liquidation of most of
his properties, and demanding that he relinquish day-to-day
control of his operations. The market value of his assets is
believed to fall well short of the amount the developer has
borrowed. Trump missed $73 million in debt payments that were
due Friday.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   UAL's nonunion workers may oppose the proposed union
buy-out of the company. Such a stance could pose a
public-relations problem for the takeover group as it seeks
financing.
   ---
   The domination of big airports by one or two airlines is
the subject of a broad Justice Department investigation into
possible antitrust violations. Prosecutors have asked USAir
for information about the allocation of gates at a new
terminal in Pittsburgh.
   ---
   An after-hours system for trading stocks and stock options
is to be announced today by the American and Cincinnati
exchanges, the Chicago Board Options Exchange and Reuters.
The alliance is a response to the Big Board's nighttime
trading plans.
   ---
   Norway's oil minister said the North Sea producer will
probably stop limiting its output, a practice begun four
years ago in a gesture of good will to OPEC. The country's
posture could rattle jittery petroleum markets.
   ---
   Factory output rose 0.6% in May as auto production
rebounded. Consumer prices increased a modest 0.2% during the
same month. Economists say the figures depict continued slow
growth with steady inflation.
                                                                                                       

   The U.S. merchandise trade gap narrowed to $6.94 billion
in April as a 6.2% plunge in imports more than offset a 3.5%
decrease in exports.
   ---
   Bond prices fell sharply Friday on a
stronger-than-expected industrial-production report, while
stocks were mixed. Broad stock-market measures ended little
changed, but the Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 7.67
points to 2935.89, a new high.
   ---
   Ford raised base prices on many cars and trucks, its first
midyear increases in three years. The move comes despite
lagging auto sales. The boosts range from $58 to $134.
   ---
   Thrift-bailout officials transferred $2.1 billion in
deposits from two insolvent S&amp;Ls to Sunbelt Savings of
Dallas. The action, intended to make government-owned Sunbelt
more attractive to potential buyers, will cost taxpayers an
estimated $1.68 billion.
   ---
   Martin A. Siegel was sentenced to two months in prison for
securities fraud. The judge cited the former Kidder Peabody
takeover strategist's cooperation in the federal government's
insider-trading probe.
   ---
   Businessland dismissed the two executives in charge of
marketing and sales, reflecting management's concern about
the computer retailer's performance in those areas.
   ---
   Hewlett-Packard today is to introduce its first
workstations incorporating the product line of Apollo
Computer, which the company acquired last year for $476.4
million.
